text: okay Gordon we don't know who you are what you do but basically could you just tell us how you became involved well four years ago I joined CEPHIT three weeks before AG con 11 I worked two movies and then AG con was the next week and basically I was just a go for it that one and the following year I was assistant house manager for Cephed Variable that's the organization that sponsors AGECOM, and I was an assistant house manager at the convention that was for the night films. And the following year, I was the full house manager for both. And this year, our chairman resigned his position in mid-October, and I took over for him in mid-October. And the majority of the work, like about 90 percent of it, has been done since then. Okay, you mentioned people like house manager and assistant house managers? The house managers, we have two house managers at AgieCon. One of them is the night films house manager. They're responsible for making sure that the movies that we show in the auditorium run smoothly and that we have workers there to keep an eye on the audience. The day house manager is responsible for getting people where they belong during the daytime at each one of the events we have scheduled. And the assistants we'll just be obviously assisting them. Right. Well, can you hear us a little bit more about what SEFID Variable is? SEFID Variable is a science fiction and fantasy committee. It's out of the student programs office here on campus, and because we are a committee, we do programming through the student programs office. Some of the other clubs on campus do their own activities and programming just for their own members, but we program for the entire university, as well as AggieCon, which is for people who aren't even members of the university. In other words, AggieCon is really done totally by students at the university, no other? About 95 percent of the officers this year are students at the university. They don't have to be. We have a few who are not. Most of them are like we have one former student, we have one person who is laying out for a few semesters while he works and that way he can become a Texas resident and not have to pay out of state tuition. and Becky Matthews who is one of our guests, we kind of count her as a member of the convention committee because she was chairman of AggieCon 11, and has helped us with the roast program this year. OK, could you tell me just a little bit about the history behind AggieCon? How many years have been in existence and what the original Aqu vessel is? OK, AggieCon number one, so far as I know, was not originally called AggieCon. It was just called the Texas A&M Science Fiction Convention, or something to that effect. They just decided it would be real fun to invite an author down and have a little miniature convention that lasted two days. I think they showed three films. I saw a report on AggieCon 4. I think AggieCon 3 was the first one that was called AggieCon. I saw a report on number four. They took in a total of $800 and spent $400. And they had two guests and showed six films total. And that was about all the programming they had. And since then, we have moved onward and upward to better and better things, to where this year we have 30 guests. We're showing eight major films at night. We have films running all day long. And we have the panels and the readings. And our budget this year is something like to take in $15,000 and to spend around $14,000 was what was budgeted. You speak of budget. Does that come from people who are registered from any school health or what? So far as the budget is concerned, we have to write up our own budget because we are an agency of the state of Texas. CFED Variable, being a committee here at the university, is a part of the state. And it's real funny because we have to turn in our budgets a year in advance before we actually even know how we did it this year's convention, as in the budget for next year has already been submitted. Okay. The planning of it, how do you start planning one, like when one convention ends and you start planning the next year immediately? How far ahead do you have to look at those? We have already sent out some letters this year asking if people would like to be guests at AggieCon 15. Some of those went out last month, as a matter of fact. So they really, they actually overlap. Okay. Do you look for a, when you plan the AggieCon, I guess the committee does the overall planning. Right. Do you look for a balance between authors, artists, you know, other kinds of people, or is it just simply anybody we can get will take? Well, usually what we like to do is there are some people, some authors here in Texas as well as some artists who are kind of like traditionalists at AggieCon. and they've been coming for several years. We try and invite all of them and usually most of them will come down here. So far as our major guests, we have the guests of honor and we have a special guest. This year we were going to have co-guests of honor. We were going to have Ann McCaffrey as well as Harry Harrison, but Ann had to back out because of medical problems. Harry Harrison was then left as our only guest of honor, which in the past we've only had one. We have our special guest, like I said. We have a Toastmaster. This year it's Dr. Chad Oliver from the University of Texas, and he will be presenting a program at the banquet this evening. He said he'd give us 15 minutes of wit and humor. And we have our artist, Guest of Honor. In addition, this year we have Don Punchotts and Real Musgrave, who are actually on the guest lineup. up we do have some other professional artists that are here they are not guests but we have uh dale harris and there's two or three others i can't remember their names at the moment that are here with work on display in the professional art gallery and we have um one person serving on panels miss victoria wheeler who is uh very good at artwork and stuff i would think she'd be termed a fan artist and she appears on both of our art panels and she is a dealer in the dealer's room. So far as the rest of it, this year we have really tried to do more stuff for the artists than we ever have in the past. Usually we have like one panel, the amateur art contest, the auction, and that's about it. And this year we've programmed two panels on art. We again have the auction and the contest. We have more judges for the contest this year than we've had in the past. What have you found to be the biggest problems in running this or planning it? The fact that all of the officers are students and we all have our homework here from the university plus all of the paperwork that is required. And I think the only reason that was a real problem at this convention was because none of the paperwork was done when I took over in mid-October. I ended up having to do the majority of the paperwork, I and my officers, at that point. Do you know how this convention compares in size other conventions in Texas? Well, we have been billed as the largest annual science fiction convention, so far as attendance is concerned. Overall, I do believe that we have a larger attendance, if you count both the one-day passes as well as the full convention passes, than what other science fiction conventions have. a lot of that is probably due to the students here on campus but we do bring in quite a few outside individuals for instance this year we had 60 non-student convention passes for the full convention that were sold in advance that means before March 1st at this particular convention I know that right right now we have a lot last night we sold, all day yesterday's total, we sold over a thousand one day passes. And I believe that the full convention passes, if you add up the students and the non-students, is probably over 500 right now. Okay, you sort of answered this and obviously I know the answer to it too but maybe a lot of people who have been listening to the show don't. Could you just briefly sort of classify the different activities as a fan coming to the convention would have. Okay, if you come to the convention, there of course are the movies. I believe they have movies at just about every science fiction convention. We have the dealer's room, which you can find just about anything and everything in there, from books to weapons to posters and other kind of paraphernalia from movies and the world of fantasy. We have the artists and the authors. They sit on panels. Some of the authors do readings for us. We had a NASA presentation yesterday. We have had one of those for the past three years, and we consider that to be pretty regular at this convention. We are having a slideshow this afternoon on Don Punschutz's artwork, and we try to have an art slideshow, or at least we've been trying to for the past three years we have the two movie companies that are here Disney and Columbia Pictures that are promoting films and I believe that since I've been here at AggieCon 12 I believe we didn't have any movie promotions but at 11 and 13 and at this one we have had movie promotions we have trivia quizzes we have the amateur art contest we have the art auction as well as other stuff that's auctioned off this year we had the world premier performance of Mr. Harry Harrison's play. That is a first, as far as I know. We also have the pro-art gallery where pro-artists can display their work and the fans can come and look at it. We have an autograph session, a guest reception, plus you can usually find the guests down in the party room if they're not doing anything else. And, let's see. Banquet? There's the banquet itself, which people can go to. Masquerade? Yeah, the masquerade we have. And there's the Neil Barrett Jr. roast this year. And last year we had the Chad Oliver roast. And I don't remember if we had a roast program the year before that, but it looks like we're starting a tradition because at A&M, if you do anything twice, it's a tradition. just a little bit more about this CFA variable that is a student a student committee it started off as a club on campus I believe you have to have at least 10 students interested in an activity that can find an advisor and you've got a club and they set you up with an account here in the student finance office you take in funds you spend money it's all recorded on paper I think back before we became an actual committee the difference in a committee being that the committees get some of their funding from the student service fees here on campus because those student service fees go for programming for all of the students on campus and whereas clubs program for their members. The committees program for the entire campus, for everyone at the university. And some of the other committees are MSC Aggie Cinema, who programs all films except those dealing with science fiction and fantasy. There is Town Hall, who they arrange for the concerts that we have over in G. Raleigh White Coliseum. there's uh opus who arranges that's um what does opus stand for something in performing arts society i forget what the o is but you can probably look it up fill in in this spot um they arrange for concerts and stage some of the stage productions and stuff like that um there's an outdoor recreation committee there's a regular recreation committee several other excellent committees that do programming here on campus and the basic difference is we program for the whole university a club just programs for itself. In other words really set the variable and the reason now for its existence is to work all year gearing up for AggieCon, that's the reason for being. That's one that's our major reason for being, however we also program all year long we show science fiction fantasy films here on campus and we are a meeting place for science fiction fantasy fans here on campus. Also on occasion we do send delegates to other conventions within the state as well as outside the state. Usually in the summertime though because most of our students are busy during the fall and spring. Could you recall just briefly a list of the ones you remember your guests of honor or special guests from the past? I'm a real bad person to ask about this. Last year, we had Roger Zelazny as our guest of honor and Fred Saberhagen was our special guest. Beyond that, I draw a complete blank even though I was here. We do have some old program books from our past conventions. We try and keep a collection of those. And anyone who's interested can certainly come up here or they could call us and we can get the information for them anytime they were interested. I do believe that AggieCon 7 was the first convention that actually had a program book. All of the others just kind of had a little schedule that was printed up on, like, one sheet of paper and put out. Now, what about your part for next year? Are you going to work on it? Next year I will be here just one semester. I will be here all summer attending the university. I will be here next fall. I'm supposed to be graduating at the end of next fall. That'll be one semester late. And I will be around to help next year's chairman if they have any questions or if next year's officers have any questions. Also, I have two other responsibilities this year. One of them is to round up all of the information that we have on this year's convention and give that to next year's officers so that they can use it in planning next year's convention. And the second item I have to do is to write up a financial report for the convention and turn that in. Are you a serious science fiction fan? Are most of the people in separate variable that way, or are they just in it for the social aspect? Both, really. The majority of the people in there are really interested in science fiction. I myself am very interested in science fiction and fantasy. and it is a pretty nice social atmosphere also. The majority of the people in the committee are real good friends and we get along real well. I would say that no one should criticize the way a science fiction fantasy convention is run until they've been on my end of the deal. Because until you have tried to set one of these things up you really don't have any understanding as to what it takes to do so. All of the paperwork and all of the correspondence that has to be done, it really is a very big job, and I'm sure that this year I could not have done it without the help of all my officers. It's worth it, isn't it? It is worth it, definitely, especially when things go right. You mentioned the authors and the guests were pretty nice people, aren't they? We have gotten a lot of compliments from them this year. They're all very nice, and a lot of them have complimented us, saying that this is a very good convention. David, Bill, you people? How many people are there in your group that are working on the call? We have, remember, 16 officers. Eight of those have assistants. And we have probably ten of what we term gophers, which means general officer for everything ridiculous. Basically, they are the peons in your organization that go and do everything that the rest of us don't have time for. And then so far as workers at the convention, just general committee members that worked, there are probably another 10 to 20 of those. What is a Cepheid variable? Oh, you already asked command. Oh, I'm sorry. You said what it is. Yeah, a Cepheid variable is a pulsating star, which there is one in the Cephas star system And if you look at it, it will appear to grow brighter and dimmer and occasionally to change colors. And that's where we took our name from. Also, our regular committee t-shirts that these Cepherd Variable people wear is kind of a play on some of the Greek fraternities. We took the letters Delta Sci-Fi, meaning changing science fiction for us here on campus that are interested in mathematics. probably the only other thing I would like to add is that for Aggie Con it tends to be real difficult from year to year for us sometimes because generally we do have almost a complete officer turnover from year to year and definitely every four years when the people who were here three years ago or four years ago graduate you lose a lot of really valuable people that know what's going on, and this year, I actually have six of my 16 officers are freshmen this year and have never even attended a science fiction convention before. Do sometimes the alumni come back and help a little bit at x Cepheid Variable? Yeah, I said earlier we have Becky Matthews, who was chairman of Aggiecon 11. Also, Steve Gould, who is one of our guests, was a member of Cefed Variable, and I believe he was a chairman at one of the conventions also. Yeah, is there anything else you can think of? Not that I know of right now. I know you're a pretty busy person. Yeah, I should probably get back. They're going to be opening up the dealer's room if they haven't already. I appreciate it very much. I appreciate your help getting us the room and everything. Listen, we'll send you tapes for this. Sure.
